	<tableOfContents displayLabel="Contents">Pt. 1. Conceptual Components -- Ch. 1. Let's Think Again -- Ch. 2. Concepts and Terms -- Ch. 3. Dimensions of the Problem -- Ch. 4. Organization of Unthinkable Systems -- Ch. 5. Hierarchies of Control -- Pt. 2. Form of the Model -- Ch. 6. Anatomy of Management -- Ch. 7. Control Physiology -- Ch. 8. Autonomy -- Ch. 9. Autonomic Management -- Ch. 10. Biggest Switch -- Pt. 3. Use of the Model -- Ch. 11. Corporate Structure and its Quantification -- Ch. 12. Autonomics -- Systems One, Two, Three -- Ch. 13. Environments of Decision -- System Four -- Ch. 14. Multinode -- System Five -- Ch. 15. Higher Management -- Pt. 4. Course of History -- Ch. 16. Flying Start -- Ch. 17. Into its Stride -- Ch. 18. October Watershed -- Ch. 19. End of the Beginning -- Ch. 20. Prospectus. Note to Part Four -- References explicit to these five chapters -- Pt. 5. Appendix.</tableOfContents>
	<abstract displayLabel="Review">"This is the second edition of a book which has already become a management standard both in universities and on the bookshelves of managers and their advisers. Brain of the Firm develops an account of the firm based upon insights derived from the study of the human nervous system, and is a basic text from the author's theory of viable systems. Despite the neurophysiology, the book is written for managers to understand. The companion volume to this book is The Heart of Enterprise, which is intended to support and complement this text."--Jacket.</abstract>
